[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1019},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F28\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F28\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F28\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F28\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity\u002F":994,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F28\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity\u002F":1003},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200628\u002F713590185\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":978,"date":979,"description":980,"extension":981,"lang":982,"meta":983,"navigation":371,"path":984,"readingMinutes":87,"seo":985,"standalone":986,"stem":987,"tags":988,"tldr":991,"updated":979,"url":992,"__hash__":993},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-16-operator-precedence-associativity.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (16) — Operators, Types & Grammar: Precedence and Associativity","1000752308",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":973},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,31,34,82,94,105,112,115,118,121,127,133,175,178,213,220,251,271,334,337,389,392,446,473,537,553,630,633,719,751,948,954,958,969],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"We covered operators last time, so now let's talk about two things that come up a lot when you're working with them: precedence and associativity.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"precedence-and-associativity","Precedence and Associativity",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":29,"src":30},"Precedence and associativity","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-06-28%2013.55.53.png",[17,32,33],{},"Let's start with a simple bit of math:",[35,36,41],"pre",{"className":37,"code":38,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 2 + 2 * 2 \u002F 2;\n","js","",[42,43,44],"code",{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,46,49,53,57,60,64,67,69,72,74,77,79],"span",{"class":47,"line":48},"line",1,[45,50,52],{"class":51},"sWyjQ","var",[45,54,56],{"class":55},"sMAXC"," a ",[45,58,59],{"class":51},"=",[45,61,63],{"class":62},"sCcAr"," 2",[45,65,66],{"class":51}," +",[45,68,63],{"class":62},[45,70,71],{"class":51}," *",[45,73,63],{"class":62},[45,75,76],{"class":51}," \u002F",[45,78,63],{"class":62},[45,80,81],{"class":55},";\n",[17,83,84,85,88,89,93],{},"I'll just give you the answer up front — it's ",[42,86,87],{},"4",". When you evaluate this, you can mostly go with your gut. In JavaScript, assignment always happens ",[90,91,92],"em",{},"after"," the right-hand side is fully evaluated, and your old math teacher's rule of \"multiply and divide before add and subtract\" kicks in. So 2 \u002F 2 = 1, then 2 * 1 = 2, and finally 2 + 2 = 4. Except... that order is actually wrong.",[17,95,96,97,104],{},"The thing is, programming languages have a defined set of rules for this that you can look up. MDN has a page called ",[98,99,103],"a",{"href":100,"rel":101},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FOperators\u002FOperator_Precedence",[102],"nofollow","Operator precedence"," that lays it all out.",[17,106,107,108,111],{},"Looking at that table, the assignment operator has a precedence level of 3 (the bigger the number, the higher the priority). The addition operator is 13. What's interesting here is that the multiplication and division operators sit at the ",[90,109,110],{},"same"," level — 14. So the order of priority looks like this:",[17,113,114],{},"3 \u003C 13 \u003C 14",[17,116,117],{},"Now you might be wondering: if multiplication and division are the same level, how does JavaScript decide which one runs first? That's where associativity comes in.",[17,119,120],{},"Associativity means that when you've got operators of the same level sitting next to each other, they run in a specific direction. And as you can see in the table, multiplication, division, and the remainder operator all evaluate left to right.",[17,122,123],{},[27,124],{"alt":125,"src":126},"Left to right","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-06-28%2014.09.10.png",[17,128,129,130,132],{},"So the correct evaluation order is: 2 * 2 first, then 4 \u002F 2, and finally 2 + 2, with the result assigned to ",[42,131,98],{},".",[35,134,136],{"className":37,"code":135,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = 2 + ((2 * 2) \u002F 2); \u002F\u002F 4\n",[42,137,138],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,139,140,142,144,146,148,150,153,156,158,160,163,166,168,171],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,141,52],{"class":51},[45,143,56],{"class":55},[45,145,59],{"class":51},[45,147,63],{"class":62},[45,149,66],{"class":51},[45,151,152],{"class":55}," ((",[45,154,155],{"class":62},"2",[45,157,71],{"class":51},[45,159,63],{"class":62},[45,161,162],{"class":55},") ",[45,164,165],{"class":51},"\u002F",[45,167,63],{"class":62},[45,169,170],{"class":55},"); ",[45,172,174],{"class":173},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 4\n",[17,176,177],{},"So why bother explaining all this? Because of another classic frontend interview question:",[35,179,181],{"className":37,"code":180,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"console.log(1 \u003C 2 \u003C 3); \u002F\u002F true\n",[42,182,183],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,184,185,188,192,195,198,201,203,205,208,210],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,186,187],{"class":55},"console.",[45,189,191],{"class":190},"sj_SG","log",[45,193,194],{"class":55},"(",[45,196,197],{"class":62},"1",[45,199,200],{"class":51}," \u003C",[45,202,63],{"class":62},[45,204,200],{"class":51},[45,206,207],{"class":62}," 3",[45,209,170],{"class":55},[45,211,212],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F true\n",[17,214,215,216,219],{},"Based on the result, the answer is definitely ",[42,217,218],{},"true"," — 1 is less than 2, and 2 is less than 3. But what about this one?",[35,221,223],{"className":37,"code":222,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"console.log(3 > 2 > 1); \u002F\u002F ?\n",[42,224,225],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,226,227,229,231,233,236,239,241,243,246,248],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,228,187],{"class":55},[45,230,191],{"class":190},[45,232,194],{"class":55},[45,234,235],{"class":62},"3",[45,237,238],{"class":51}," >",[45,240,63],{"class":62},[45,242,238],{"class":51},[45,244,245],{"class":62}," 1",[45,247,170],{"class":55},[45,249,250],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F ?\n",[17,252,253,254,257,258,261,262,264,265,267,268,270],{},"This one outputs ",[42,255,256],{},"false",". And sure, 3 ",[90,259,260],{},"is"," greater than 2, and 2 ",[90,263,260],{}," greater than 1, so what gives? This is where associativity meets type coercion. We're using comparison operators here, and a comparison operator returns either ",[42,266,218],{}," or ",[42,269,256],{},". According to MDN's associativity table, the less-than (and greater-than) operator evaluates left to right, so if we break it apart it looks like this:",[35,272,274],{"className":37,"code":273,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"console.log(3 > 2); \u002F\u002F true\nconsole.log(true > 1); \u002F\u002F heads up — type coercion happens here, and true = 1, so this is really 1 > 1\nconsole.log(1 > 1); \u002F\u002F false, because 1 is not greater than 1\n",[42,275,276,294,314],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,277,278,280,282,284,286,288,290,292],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,279,187],{"class":55},[45,281,191],{"class":190},[45,283,194],{"class":55},[45,285,235],{"class":62},[45,287,238],{"class":51},[45,289,63],{"class":62},[45,291,170],{"class":55},[45,293,212],{"class":173},[45,295,297,299,301,303,305,307,309,311],{"class":47,"line":296},2,[45,298,187],{"class":55},[45,300,191],{"class":190},[45,302,194],{"class":55},[45,304,218],{"class":62},[45,306,238],{"class":51},[45,308,245],{"class":62},[45,310,170],{"class":55},[45,312,313],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F heads up — type coercion happens here, and true = 1, so this is really 1 > 1\n",[45,315,317,319,321,323,325,327,329,331],{"class":47,"line":316},3,[45,318,187],{"class":55},[45,320,191],{"class":190},[45,322,194],{"class":55},[45,324,197],{"class":62},[45,326,238],{"class":51},[45,328,245],{"class":62},[45,330,170],{"class":55},[45,332,333],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F false, because 1 is not greater than 1\n",[17,335,336],{},"Now let's look at one more case, this time with assignment:",[35,338,340],{"className":37,"code":339,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = 1;\nvar b = 2;\n\na = b = 1;\n",[42,341,342,354,367,373],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,343,344,346,348,350,352],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,345,52],{"class":51},[45,347,56],{"class":55},[45,349,59],{"class":51},[45,351,245],{"class":62},[45,353,81],{"class":55},[45,355,356,358,361,363,365],{"class":47,"line":296},[45,357,52],{"class":51},[45,359,360],{"class":55}," b ",[45,362,59],{"class":51},[45,364,63],{"class":62},[45,366,81],{"class":55},[45,368,369],{"class":47,"line":316},[45,370,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},true,"\n",[45,374,376,379,381,383,385,387],{"class":47,"line":375},4,[45,377,378],{"class":55},"a ",[45,380,59],{"class":51},[45,382,360],{"class":55},[45,384,59],{"class":51},[45,386,245],{"class":62},[45,388,81],{"class":55},[17,390,391],{},"Per MDN, the assignment operator's associativity is right to left, so breaking it apart looks like this:",[35,393,395],{"className":37,"code":394,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = 1;\nvar b = 2;\n\nb = 1;\na = b;\n",[42,396,397,409,421,425,436],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,398,399,401,403,405,407],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,400,52],{"class":51},[45,402,56],{"class":55},[45,404,59],{"class":51},[45,406,245],{"class":62},[45,408,81],{"class":55},[45,410,411,413,415,417,419],{"class":47,"line":296},[45,412,52],{"class":51},[45,414,360],{"class":55},[45,416,59],{"class":51},[45,418,63],{"class":62},[45,420,81],{"class":55},[45,422,423],{"class":47,"line":316},[45,424,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},[45,426,427,430,432,434],{"class":47,"line":375},[45,428,429],{"class":55},"b ",[45,431,59],{"class":51},[45,433,245],{"class":62},[45,435,81],{"class":55},[45,437,439,441,443],{"class":47,"line":438},5,[45,440,378],{"class":55},[45,442,59],{"class":51},[45,444,445],{"class":55}," b;\n",[17,447,448,449,451,452,455,456,459,460,462,463,465,466,468,469,472],{},"The logic looks right, and it lines up with the assignment operator's associativity. But it's actually wrong. Here's what's really happening: ",[42,450,98],{}," receives the ",[90,453,454],{},"result"," returned by ",[42,457,458],{},"b = 1",". We know ",[42,461,458],{}," returns a value, because it's an expression — so ",[42,464,98],{}," is actually receiving the value that ",[42,467,458],{}," returns, not directly grabbing ",[42,470,471],{},"b","'s value. That's a pretty special detail, so let's look at another example:",[35,474,476],{"className":37,"code":475,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = {};\n\nObject.defineProperty(a, 'b', {\n  value: 0,\n  writable: false,\n})\n",[42,477,478,489,493,511,522,531],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,479,480,482,484,486],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,481,52],{"class":51},[45,483,56],{"class":55},[45,485,59],{"class":51},[45,487,488],{"class":55}," {};\n",[45,490,491],{"class":47,"line":296},[45,492,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},[45,494,495,498,501,504,508],{"class":47,"line":316},[45,496,497],{"class":55},"Object.",[45,499,500],{"class":190},"defineProperty",[45,502,503],{"class":55},"(a, ",[45,505,507],{"class":506},"sTRMh","'b'",[45,509,510],{"class":55},", {\n",[45,512,513,516,519],{"class":47,"line":375},[45,514,515],{"class":55},"  value: ",[45,517,518],{"class":62},"0",[45,520,521],{"class":55},",\n",[45,523,524,527,529],{"class":47,"line":438},[45,525,526],{"class":55},"  writable: ",[45,528,256],{"class":62},[45,530,521],{"class":55},[45,532,534],{"class":47,"line":533},6,[45,535,536],{"class":55},"})\n",[17,538,539,540,543,544,546,547,549,550,552],{},"Here we used ",[42,541,542],{},"Object.defineProperty"," to give ",[42,545,98],{}," a property ",[42,548,471],{}," with a value of ",[42,551,518],{},", set so it can't be modified again.",[35,554,556],{"className":37,"code":555,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = {};\n\nObject.defineProperty(a, 'b', {\n  value: 0,\n  writable: false,\n})\na.b = 10;\nconsole.log(a.b); \u002F\u002F 0\n",[42,557,558,568,572,584,592,600,604,617],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,559,560,562,564,566],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,561,52],{"class":51},[45,563,56],{"class":55},[45,565,59],{"class":51},[45,567,488],{"class":55},[45,569,570],{"class":47,"line":296},[45,571,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},[45,573,574,576,578,580,582],{"class":47,"line":316},[45,575,497],{"class":55},[45,577,500],{"class":190},[45,579,503],{"class":55},[45,581,507],{"class":506},[45,583,510],{"class":55},[45,585,586,588,590],{"class":47,"line":375},[45,587,515],{"class":55},[45,589,518],{"class":62},[45,591,521],{"class":55},[45,593,594,596,598],{"class":47,"line":438},[45,595,526],{"class":55},[45,597,256],{"class":62},[45,599,521],{"class":55},[45,601,602],{"class":47,"line":533},[45,603,536],{"class":55},[45,605,607,610,612,615],{"class":47,"line":606},7,[45,608,609],{"class":55},"a.b ",[45,611,59],{"class":51},[45,613,614],{"class":62}," 10",[45,616,81],{"class":55},[45,618,620,622,624,627],{"class":47,"line":619},8,[45,621,187],{"class":55},[45,623,191],{"class":190},[45,625,626],{"class":55},"(a.b); ",[45,628,629],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F 0\n",[17,631,632],{},"So how do we prove that the assignment operator receives the returned expression value? Like this:",[35,634,636],{"className":37,"code":635,"language":39,"meta":40,"style":40},"var a = {};\n\nObject.defineProperty(a, 'b', {\n  value: 0,\n  writable: false,\n})\n\nvar c = a.b = 10;\nconsole.log(c); \u002F\u002F 10\n",[42,637,638,648,652,664,672,680,684,688,706],{"__ignoreMap":40},[45,639,640,642,644,646],{"class":47,"line":48},[45,641,52],{"class":51},[45,643,56],{"class":55},[45,645,59],{"class":51},[45,647,488],{"class":55},[45,649,650],{"class":47,"line":296},[45,651,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},[45,653,654,656,658,660,662],{"class":47,"line":316},[45,655,497],{"class":55},[45,657,500],{"class":190},[45,659,503],{"class":55},[45,661,507],{"class":506},[45,663,510],{"class":55},[45,665,666,668,670],{"class":47,"line":375},[45,667,515],{"class":55},[45,669,518],{"class":62},[45,671,521],{"class":55},[45,673,674,676,678],{"class":47,"line":438},[45,675,526],{"class":55},[45,677,256],{"class":62},[45,679,521],{"class":55},[45,681,682],{"class":47,"line":533},[45,683,536],{"class":55},[45,685,686],{"class":47,"line":606},[45,687,372],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":371},[45,689,690,692,695,697,700,702,704],{"class":47,"line":619},[45,691,52],{"class":51},[45,693,694],{"class":55}," c ",[45,696,59],{"class":51},[45,698,699],{"class":55}," a.b ",[45,701,59],{"class":51},[45,703,614],{"class":62},[45,705,81],{"class":55},[45,707,709,711,713,716],{"class":47,"line":708},9,[45,710,187],{"class":55},[45,712,191],{"class":190},[45,714,715],{"class":55},"(c); ",[45,717,718],{"class":173},"\u002F\u002F 10\n",[17,720,721,722,725,726,729,730,733,734,737,738,740,741,743,744,747,748,750],{},"Writing it this way confirms that ",[42,723,724],{},"c"," directly receives the result the expression returns. When the right side runs first, ",[42,727,728],{},"a.b = 10;"," returns a result of ",[42,731,732],{},"10"," — but it can't actually modify the value, so ",[42,735,736],{},"a.b"," stays ",[42,739,518],{}," (we already knew that). So ",[42,742,724],{}," is receiving the ",[90,745,746],{},"returned result",", not ",[42,749,736],{},"'s actual value. The core idea here is really about expressions. And o